{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491406"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:46:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:46:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"933"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/933"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.52,0.16,0.01,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"933"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81007"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/933"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"933"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66339"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"577"},{"type":"tags","id":"1772"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"254"},{"type":"contributions","id":"680"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12160"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81007"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a large multinodular goitre that has been present for many years. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The goitre is visible and palpable in the anterior neck. There are no signs of thyroid dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following clinical signs would be most suggestive of retrosternal extension of the goitre?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tracheal deviation on examination","Pemberton\u0027s sign","Hoarseness of voice","Elevated jugular venous pressure","Inability to palpate the lower thyroid margin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a long-standing multinodular goitre requiring assessment for retrosternal extension. The thoracic inlet is a confined anatomical space bounded by the first ribs, manubrium, and first thoracic vertebra, containing vital structures including major vessels, nerves, trachea and oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPemberton\u0027s sign\u003C/strong\u003E (Facial plethora on raising arms) is the most specific clinical sign of retrosternal extension. When the patient raises their arms, the clavicles move medially and inferiorly, compressing any retrosternal thyroid tissue against the thoracic inlet. This compression results in venous obstruction and facial plethora.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETracheal deviation\u003C/strong\u003E may occur with any large goitre and is not specific for retrosternal extension. The trachea can be displaced by thyroid masses that are entirely cervical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHoarseness of voice\u003C/strong\u003E suggests recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement, which is more commonly associated with malignant infiltration rather than benign compression from a retrosternal goitre.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevated jugular venous pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is typically associated with cardiac pathology. While venous distension can occur with superior vena cava obstruction, this finding alone is not specific for retrosternal goitre.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInability to palpate the lower thyroid margin\u003C/strong\u003E is an unreliable sign as it depends heavily on neck position and examiner technique. It does not definitively indicate retrosternal extension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pemberton\u0027s sign (facial plethora on raising arms) is the most specific clinical sign of retrosternal goitre extension","The thoracic inlet is a confined space where slowly growing goitres can compress vital structures, particularly veins","Tracheal deviation and inability to palpate the lower thyroid margin are unreliable signs of retrosternal extension"],"references":["De Filippis EA, Sabet A, Sun MRM, et al. Pemberton\u2019s Sign: Explained Nearly 70 Years Later. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2014;99:1949-54. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24646105/","Talley NJ, O\u2019Connor S. Talley and O\u2019Connor\u2019s Clinical Examination. 9th edition. Elsevier; 2021"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66339"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"933"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66339"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-24T21:17:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-24T21:17:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"933"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81007"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"att